com.camerontec.util.datamodel.expression.compiler.functions

Interface Function

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    Abs, AsInteger, Ceil, Contains, EndsWith, Floor, GetExponent, InsertInto, Length, Max, Min, Now, Pow, Random, RandomInteger, RInt, Round, Signum, Split, StartsWith, Timezone, TimezoneDiff, ToBytes, ToLowerCase, ToUpperCase, Trim

    public interface Function
    Instances of this interface are functions supported by the expression language.
    Functions expose their metadata, as seen from the perspective of the expression compiler, through method getMetadata() and are implicitly expected to expose a number of public static invoke() methods, each corresponding to a supported signature, in order for compiled code to invoke that function.

    The metadata returned by getMetadata() must obey the following rules:
    • Duplicated parameter names are not allowed.
    • If the function is declared to use vararg parameters, then it must have at least one parameter.
    • If the function has multiple signatures, their parameters types must be different. In other words, two signatures are not allowed to differ only by their return types.
    The signatures of the function's invoke() methods must be derived from the function's signatures as follows:
    • The first parameter of all invoke() methods must be of type ExpressionValuesFactory. This is the factory to use for creating new values if required.
    • Other parameter types and the return type are translated from expression data types to Java data types as per the following table:

      Expression data type Java data type
      boolean boolean
      boolean[] BooleanArrayList
      int long
      utc-timestamp
      int[] LongArrayList
      utc-timstamp[]
      float MutableCompactDecimal
      float[] DecimalArrayList
      char char
      char[] CharArrayList
      string MutableString
      endpoint
      string[] StringArrayList
      endpoint[]
      byte[] ByteArrayView
      field IntegerArrayList
      range Range


    • If the function is declared to use vararg parameters, then the last parameter of method invoke() must be an array of the Java data type given by the above table.
    For example:
    • For a function not using vararg parameters and a signature expressed as integer f(field, utc-timestamp[]), then the signature of method invoke() must be:
      public static long invoke(ExpressionValueFactory factory, IntegerArrayList p1, LongArrayList p2).
    • For the same function but using vararg parameters the signature of method invoke() must be:
      public static long invoke(ExpressionValueFactory factory, IntegerArrayList p1, LongArrayList[] p2).
    The implementation of a function's invoke() can throw any type of Throwable to report error conditions. At execution time, any caught Throwable is wrapped into an ExpressionEvaluationException.
